<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Cycling Tynedale (CYS0012)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Cycling Tynedale</span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> (CYS0012)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">There are already good guidelines promoting increased cycling and walking for both economic, health and welfare benefits. e.g. NICE guidelines PH8 and 41 are directed towards planners, highways agencies, etc. But in our area, Northumberland, the individual</span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">s in power are either not aware of best practise or ignore it. </span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt"> Finances are a commonly held barrier to implementation of change, yet we have examples of considerable Highways spend where no consideration whatsoever was made to opportunistic inclusion of c</span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">hanges to improve cycling</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">We therefore think there needs to be a statutory requirement for Local Authorities to consider safe cycling provision in everything they do and implement safe cycling unless there are good reason not to.</span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt"> It is </span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">important for the population of those areas who have not received government funding for cycling or do not have suitably visionary councils that central government impetus is given. The ‘how’ can be a local decision, ‘whether or not’ should not be an optio</span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">n.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">We request that to enable the implementation of NICE guidelines of all journeys less than 5 miles by default to be by walking or cycling and less than 1 mile to be by walking, that every</span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt"> location with a population of greater than 500 people should have</span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt"> a safe, separated from road, walking and cycling route, to any other population centre of greater than 500 people within 5 miles; and for a safe on road route for populations greater than 100 people.  Local Authorities should be mandated to plan for this </span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">and implement within a 10 year framework.</span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">Access rights. Concerns over the difficulty of getting agreement for a cycle route to pass over a part of land are an important barrier and an oft stated reason for doing </span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">nothing. We think ROWIP should be support</span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">ed such that the presumption is always in favour of creation of new cycle routes where such routes would help fulfill NICE guidelines, support utility cycling or cycle tourism.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">Silo thinking. Cycling touches many different areas of government. Education, </span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">transport, planning, tourism, health, leisure. This can sometimes mean no-one takes an over-arching strategic view and one group blocks another. It is therefore important that the committee mandates cross cutting steering groups with teeth that can draw di</span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">fferent interest groups together and push forward change.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">Highways mythology. Many changes we have proposed have been rejected by local councilors on the basis of ‘not allowed because of DfT regulations’. Yet when we explore, much appears to be local inte</span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">rpretations or individual implementations. There is thus a risk of learned helplessness that nothing can be done. A mechanism to overcome local intransigence is therefore needed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11pt">e.g. widespread recognition of need for safe, off road cycle route alon</span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11pt">g Tyne Valley, yet when A695, which follows this route, was resurfaced this year, no consideration of possible improvements for cyclists or pedestrians was made. This information was obtained under FOI. If improvements had been considered but rejected for </span><span style="color:#3f3f3f; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11pt">particular reasons this would have been more understandable, so when the default response from local councilors is ‘no money’, that improvements were not even considered is immensely frustrating.</span></p></body></html>